    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>The danger of moist and wet avalanches will increase a little during the day.</highlights>
      <comment>Early morning: The surface of the snowpack will freeze to form a strong crust and will soften later than the day before. In steep terrain there is a danger of falling on the hard snow surface. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> In the course of the day the natural activity of avalanches will gradually increase. &lt;br/> In particular in starting zones where no previous releases have taken place and on very steep shady slopes more small and medium-sized natural wet avalanches are possible. &lt;br/> The conditions are generally favourable for ski touring. Backcountry tours and ascents to alpine cabins should be concluded timely. &lt;br/> The near-surface layers of the snowpack can be released in isolated cases by winter sport participants in particular in extremely steep terrain.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>In the last two days the wind was moderate at times especially along the border with France. &lt;br/> The weather conditions gave rise to rapid settling of the snowpack. &lt;br/> This situation gave rise to moistening of the snowpack below approximately 2500 m. &lt;br/> The amount of snow is subject to significant local variations. &lt;br/> In particular below the tree line hardly any snow is lying on southeast and southwest facing slopes. &lt;br/> Especially at high altitudes and in high Alpine regions there is still a very large amount of snow. &lt;br/> Weak layers exist in the snowpack in particular on steep shady slopes.</comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
    <travelAdvisory/>
    <tendency>
      <highlights>As the temperature drops only isolated moist and wet avalanches are possible.</highlights>
      <tendencyType>decreasing</tendencyType>
